signature.instructions:
Evaluate the supplied Magic: The Gathering card for the supplied deck and return exactly one valid JSON object with these fields, in this order:

"overall_summary", "land", "mana_ramp", "card_advantage", "card_selection", "targeted_disruption", "mass_disruption", "enabler", "payoff", "enhancer"

INPUT

The supplied evaluation_context contains:

- a North Star describing the deck’s plan;
- cards explicitly referenced by that North Star or by card notes;
- the card under evaluation, including name, mana cost, type line, power/toughness, and Oracle text;
- role definitions and rubric criterion IDs.

Use only the supplied card’s printed information, the North Star, explicitly supplied referenced cards, role definitions, and rubric criteria. Do not infer unmentioned cards, quantities, commanders, mechanics, zones, triggers, costs, card types, recursion, landfall, fetch effects, sacrifice outlets, or synergies. Do not encode or memorize individual card names in these instructions; reason from mechanics and supplied context.

OUTPUT

Return exactly one JSON object, with no commentary, markdown, explanation, code fence, or second object.

For every role the card does not materially fulfill, use exactly:

"N/A"

For every applicable role, use:

{
  "description": "Exactly one concise mechanics-based sentence of approximately 20–40 words.",
  "answers": {
    "criterion_id": "very_low | low | neutral | high | very_high"
  }
}

The answers keys must exactly match that role’s supplied rubric criterion IDs, with no missing or additional keys. Use ordinary JSON strings, not Python representations, enums, class names, or single-quoted fields.

GENERAL ROLE RULES

1. Apply every role definition and exclusion strictly.

2. A card may fill multiple roles only when the roles represent genuinely distinct underlying behaviors. Do not assign two roles to the same draw, retrieval, removal, protection, or mana behavior.

3. Mark a role applicable only when the card materially performs that job in this deck. If most criteria would be low or very_low, return "N/A" unless the role definition makes the weak criterion intrinsic to the effect.

4. Rate each criterion against all cards in this format that perform that role, not against an empty deck slot:
   - "very_high": among the strongest printed examples;
   - "high": clearly above average;
   - "neutral": typical;
   - "low": below average;
   - "very_low": barely applicable or exceptionally weak.

5. If every answer for an applicable role is high or very_high, re-check the evaluation. Most real cards have at least one typical or weak dimension.

6. Ground every statement in printed mechanics and explicitly established deck context.

7. Do not treat incidental, negligible, generic, or hypothetical functionality as a role.

8. A modal double-faced card with a land face may receive land treatment and, independently, spell roles for a spell face that satisfies those roles.

9. A land is applicable only when the type line explicitly includes Land, including a modal double-faced card with a land face.

10. Most cards should materially fill one or two roles. Returning "N/A" for every role is correct when all effects are generic or fail the materiality threshold.

CARD ACCESS AND OVERLAP

Distinguish card advantage from card selection by net card access.

CARD ADVANTAGE:
- Applies when one card spent produces more than one card of real access.
- Includes multi-card draw, repeatable draw engines, impulse draw that permits playing the cards, recurring land retrieval, repeatable playing or copying of real cards from graveyards, and self-mill only when the North Star explicitly establishes reliable graveyard use.
- A permanent that enters and retrieves or draws a card qualifies when the permanent remains in play and the card is retained, because both the permanent and retrieved card contribute to access.
- A dig or mill effect qualifies when it finishes with at least two cards in hand.
- A recurring effect qualifies cumulatively when it repeatedly produces extra cards over the game.

Do NOT assign card advantage to:
- a one-shot tutor, chosen retrieval, or one-shot reanimation that exchanges one card for exactly one chosen card;
- a cantrip or replacement draw whose net access is one card;
- a permanent whose only draw happens later when it dies, is sacrificed, or is otherwise cashed in, because the delayed card replaces the spent permanent rather than being held alongside it at the time of the exchange;
- tokens, because tokens are not cards;
- conditional optional draw-doubling effects when the role definition identifies them as enhancers.

A delayed death-trigger draw may be described as a limitation, floor, or resilience feature of another genuine role, but it cannot itself make card_advantage applicable.

CARD SELECTION:
- Applies to net-neutral filtering, ordering, scry, surveil, cantrips with meaningful filtering, top-library manipulation, one-card tutors, and one-shot chosen retrieval or reanimation.
- A one-shot effect that exchanges the spell for exactly one chosen card belongs here, not card_advantage.
- Do not assign card_selection to raw draw with no meaningful choice, filtering, or ordering.
- Do not assign card_selection alongside card_advantage for the same multi-card draw, dig, or retrieval behavior.
- When a card’s choice is part of obtaining extra cards, that choice belongs to card_advantage rather than card_selection.
- Conditional draw engines that generate extra access and permit choosing which drawn cards remain in hand are still card_advantage or enhancer behavior according to the role definitions; the selection involved in retaining cards is not a separate card_selection role.

MANA RAMP

Apply when the card gives more available mana than the natural one-land-per-turn progression. This includes mana dorks, mana rocks, permanent land-ramp spells, reliable extra land drops, broad cost reduction, repeatable land-return engines, and resource-token engines. A one-shot ramp spell qualifies when it leaves a permanent land or mana source.

Exclude:
- lands themselves, including fetch lands;
- tutors that find cards without producing mana;
- an extra land play that only offsets a land sacrificed each turn;
- genuinely one-shot burst mana that disappears the same turn, unless the North Star explicitly builds around one large turn.

LAND

For an applicable land, judge the land face first using the supplied land rubric. A land’s separate non-mana ability may also receive a matching role:
- graveyard exile: mass_disruption;
- channel removal: targeted_disruption;
- surveil or scry: card_selection only when the deck explicitly uses the graveyard or the effect otherwise satisfies the supplied selection definition.

ENABLER

An enabler performs plan-specific work the deck’s core plan depends on, such as creating, fueling, assembling, recurring, rebuilding, or protecting the plan. Protection includes explicitly printed hexproof, indestructible, regeneration, haste, or flash when those abilities preserve the deck’s key pieces.

Apply the staple test:
- generic lands, fixing, ramp, mana dorks, mana rocks, burst mana, removal, countermagic, ordinary draw, ordinary filtering, and ordinary interaction are not enablers merely because the deck uses mana, cards, lands, or protection;
- a separate, explicitly supported graveyard-fueling, recursion, rebuilding, or protection behavior can qualify;
- every card of a class triggering the deck’s plan in the same generic way is not thereby plan-specific;
- an effect that taxes or disrupts opponents may qualify only for a distinct, explicitly supported plan function; count the opposing-card interaction itself as disruption, not enabler protection.

PAYOFF

A payoff rewards the plan after it is active by converting assembled activity into damage, cards, mana, board presence, disruption, inevitability, or a win. Do not call a card a payoff merely because it is useful before the plan is assembled or helps establish the plan.

ENHANCER

An enhancer multiplies an existing plan or repeated output, such as token, damage, trigger, or draw doublers and similar amplifiers. It should have little meaningful independent function relative to the deck’s plan.

A card that directly creates the plan’s resources, directly draws extra cards as its principal effect, or directly produces the payoff is not automatically an enhancer for that same behavior. However, when the supplied role definition explicitly classifies a conditional draw-doubling effect as an enhancer, prioritize that classification over card_advantage and card_selection for the same draw behavior.

DISRUPTION

TARGETED_DISRUPTION applies to a one-card, one-for-one answer against one opponent’s individual card or play, including spot removal, stack interaction, bounce, taps, freezes, targeted graveyard exile, or single-land disruption. Repeated use remains targeted when each use affects one opposing object or play.

MASS_DISRUPTION applies when one card answers many cards at once or affects each opponent simultaneously, including wipes, global resets, mass artifact or enchantment removal, graveyard exile, each-opponent sacrifice or discard, fogs, attack taxes, stax, silence effects, or full-turn lockouts. Apply the supplied parity test to determine whether the effect leaves the deck level with the table or behind.

Protection of the deck’s own cards is enabler behavior, never disruption. Do not assign both targeted_disruption and mass_disruption to the same underlying effect.

WRITING RESTRICTIONS

1. Every applicable role description must be exactly one sentence of approximately 20–40 words.

2. Each description must be mechanics-based, deck-specific, concise, and consistent with its ratings.

3. Mention limitations only within the behavior of that applicable role. Do not contrast an applicable role with roles rated "N/A" or with unrelated absent functions.

4. Do not use any of these phrases anywhere in overall_summary or any role description:
   - "offers no"
   - "does not provide"
   - "lacks"
   - "adds no"
   - "not a"
   - "just a"
   - "merely"
   - "rather than"

5. Do not describe abilities absent from the card’s Oracle text or unsupported synergies.

6. overall_summary must be exactly one concise sentence describing only the card’s strongest applicable roles and an important limitation within those roles. Do not mention a role rated "N/A" or a role whose ratings are predominantly low. If no role is applicable, summarize only the card’s relevant generic function without inventing a role.

7. Do not mention card names other than the supplied card when needed for the supplied North Star or referenced-card context.

FINAL VALIDATION

Before returning the object, verify all of the following:

- all ten fields appear exactly once and in the required order;
- every non-applicable role is exactly the string "N/A";
- every applicable role contains exactly one 20–40-word sentence and an answers object;
- every answers key exactly matches the supplied rubric IDs;
- every rating is exactly one of "very_low", "low", "neutral", "high", or "very_high";
- the output is valid JSON with double quotes and no extra text;
- no forbidden phrase appears;
- no unsupported mechanic, synergy, zone, card, or quantity appears;
- delayed replacement draw from a death or sacrifice trigger is not card_advantage;
- a permanent that enters and retains both its body and a retrieved or drawn card can be card_advantage;
- one-shot chosen retrieval of exactly one card is card_selection, not card_advantage;
- card_selection is not duplicated for the same multi-card advantage behavior;
- conditional draw-doubling effects classified as enhancers are not also assigned card_advantage or card_selection for that same draw behavior;
- generic staples are not labeled enablers solely because the deck uses the relevant generic resource;
- no role is assigned solely for hypothetical or incidental functionality.
